 {"id":"br-r37-c1-5nop9","title":"parity: bfs_labeled_edges public signature should be (G, sources) matching networkx","description":"fnx.bfs_labeled_edges has signature (G, sources=None, sort_neighbors=None, *, source=None) — three problems vs nx (G, sources): sources is required in nx but optional here, sort_neighbors is not part of upstream signature, source is a keyword-only legacy alias. Even though both shapes appear to function, the public signature divergence is observable via inspect.signature, breaks parameter introspection used by typed wrappers, and means typer-style strict argument routing breaks. Tighten the wrapper to (G, sources) matching nx; if downstream callers pass sort_neighbors/source those are unsupported by nx and should fail loudly.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T01:09:39.386409859Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T03:16:47.912406594Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T03:16:47.910554548Z","close_reason":"Shipped in bf5195e: bfs_labeled_edges sig tightened to (G, sources). Removed sort_neighbors and source= legacy params. 3 existing tests still pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-5npb6","title":"parity: Graph class method signatures hidden by @wraps decorator on top of Rust-bound methods","description":"Many Graph/DiGraph/MultiGraph/MultiDiGraph methods are wrapped via @wraps(rust_impl) — the Rust impl has signature () so functools.wraps overwrites the Python wrapper's documented signature with the catch-all. inspect.signature(g.to_directed) returns () instead of (self, as_view=False). 53 method-signature drifts surface across the four Graph classes: add_edge (u_of_edge, v_of_edge), add_node (node_for_adding), add_weighted_edges_from (ebunch_to_add), remove_node (n vs node), remove_nodes_from (nodes vs bunch), remove_edges_from (ebunch vs bunch), edges/nodes/get_edge_data (args/kwargs vs documented surface), to_directed/to_undirected (missing as_view kwarg in introspection). Fix: replace @wraps(rust_impl) with @wraps(nx_method) where appropriate, OR drop wraps and manually set __doc__/__name__, OR delete __wrapped__ on the wrapper. Add parity tests asserting inspect.signature(method) matches nx for all four classes.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T05:14:17.351791844Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T05:17:19.848195304Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T05:17:19.846339454Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit 2026bc3. Dropped @wraps(rust_impl) from to_directed/to_undirected wrappers (rust impls have empty () signatures that poisoned inspect.signature via __wrapped__). Now inspect.signature(g.to_directed) returns nx's (as_view=False) and DiGraph.to_undirected returns (reciprocal=False, as_view=False). 11 parity tests freeze the contract. Note: this is a partial fix for the broader 53-method drift sweep — remaining drifts (add_edge/add_node parameter names, edges/nodes/get_edge_data catch-all from PyO3 bindings) need separate beads since they require Rust binding changes or per-method Python wrappers.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-5q77h","title":"parity: bipartite matching/cluster/basic/redundancy wrappers missing (12 functions)","description":"networkx.algorithms.bipartite exposes 12 functions not surfaced by franken_networkx: matching family (eppstein_matching, maximum_matching, minimum_weight_full_matching, to_vertex_cover), cluster family (cc_dot, cc_max, cc_min, latapy_clustering, robins_alexander_clustering), basic (degrees, sets), and redundancy (node_redundancy). Add Python wrappers in __init__.py via a new _call_networkx_bipartite_for_parity helper, export at top-level, add to __all__ under bipartite section.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-25T20:04:07.582914231Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-25T20:21:47.577934437Z","closed_at":"2026-04-25T20:21:47.575865893Z","close_reason":"Shipped in f6a631a: 12 bipartite wrappers via _call_networkx_bipartite_for_parity helper (cc_dot/cc_max/cc_min routed through nx.algorithms.bipartite.cluster). All verified against nx on K33 + weighted 3x3 bipartite graph.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"br-r37-c1-5ur50","title":"parity: all_pairs_shortest_path/_length inner dicts iterate in wrong order, nx uses BFS-from-source order","description":"fnx.all_pairs_shortest_path and fnx.shortest_path_length(no source/target) yield outer dict keys in correct (node-insertion) order, but each per-source INNER dict iterates in arbitrary Rust internal order. nx returns inner dicts in BFS-visit-from-source order at each source. Same iteration-order family as br-r37-c1-tlrdu (single_source_shortest_path). Drop-in code that does 'for src in result: for tgt, dist in result[src].items(): ...' breaks. Fix: reorder each inner dict using the same _bfs_visit_order helper.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T11:28:15.930496096Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T11:30:59.049329201Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T11:30:59.047325374Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit 013e861. all_pairs_shortest_path/_length and shortest_path_length(no args) now return inner dicts in BFS-visit-from-source order matching nx. 7 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-62jy2","title":"parity: 7 more single_source_* path/length functions yield dict in wrong order vs nx's distance-order","description":"fnx.single_source_dijkstra_path / _length / single_source_dijkstra (tuple), fnx.single_source_bellman_ford_path / _length / single_source_bellman_ford (tuple), and fnx.shortest_path(G, source=...) all yield outer dict keys in arbitrary Rust internal order. nx returns the dict with keys sorted by ascending shortest-path distance from source (with adj-order tiebreak). Drop-in code that iterates 'for tgt, path in single_source_dijkstra_path(...).items(): ...' breaks. Same iteration-order family. Fix: sort by distance from the corresponding _length call (stable sort preserves tiebreak).","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T10:56:27.188576357Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T11:01:07.554842923Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T11:01:07.552821843Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit d5e47eb. 7 single_source dijkstra/BF functions and shortest_path(source=...) now iterate in (distance, BFS-tiebreak) order matching nx exactly. 10 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-64e9i","title":"parity: random_clustered_graph positional arg order swapped (seq,seed,create_using vs nx seq,create_using,seed)","description":"fnx had (joint_degree_sequence, seed, create_using) while nx has (joint_degree_sequence, create_using, seed). Drop-in callers passing positional args got swapped semantics. Reproducer: fnx.random_clustered_graph(seq, fnx.MultiGraph, 42) raised 'create_using is not a valid NetworkX graph type' because seed=MultiGraph (class) and create_using=42 (int). Same call worked on nx. Reordered fnx signature to match nx exactly. 4 parity tests freeze the contract.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T03:39:30.030984077Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T03:40:14.601137178Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T03:40:14.599133946Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit dbe62f6. Positional order now matches nx (joint_degree_sequence, create_using, seed). 4 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-682kr","title":"parity: 7 traversal/path/clique iterators return list/list_iterator instead of generator","description":"fnx.all_simple_paths, shortest_simple_paths, enumerate_all_cliques, find_cliques, bfs_edges, dfs_edges, lexicographical_topological_sort all return list or list_iterator (eager materialisation in Rust) while nx returns true generators (lazy). Drop-in code doing isinstance(result, types.GeneratorType) breaks; short-circuit patterns like next(all_simple_paths(huge_graph, ...)) materialise the entire result on fnx vs. one path on nx — could be unbounded. Same root fix as br-r37-c1-lby4x (isolates): wrap the Rust impl with 'yield from' so the returned object is a true generator. Side-benefit: error timing now matches nx (raised on first iteration, not on call).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T06:49:40.714200195Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T06:53:49.084210390Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T06:53:49.081967434Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit 584aa80. all_simple_paths, shortest_simple_paths, enumerate_all_cliques, find_cliques, find_cliques_recursive, bfs_edges, dfs_edges, and lexicographical_topological_sort now return true generators matching nx's lazy contract. 23 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
